{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608725/1958030901/0596.xml":{"full_text":"A-8\nTH* SUNDAY STAN, Wuhtnfton, D. C.\nIVNMT. UUH S. INI\nLong Pull to Recovery\nIndicated by Survey\nBy STERLING F. GREEN AND NORMAN WALKER\nAuoolateO Prat Rue Wrilm\nFrom Main Street to Wall Street Americans seem far less\nconfident than President Eisenhower\u2019s administration that\nAllins business soon will solve its troubles on its own.\nThe generally prevailing opinion found by The Associated\nPress in a Nationwide \u201cHow\u2019s Business?\u201d survey is that the\neconomy faces a long, bard pull toward recovery.\nThese other grassroots sentiments were found to be wide*\nspread:\n1. If an early recovery is to\nbe achieved, vigorous Federal\naction will be needed\u2014perhaps\na tax reduction to boost buy\nine power.\nr 2. Unemployment\u2014now at or\nshove 5 million\u2014will continue\nat painfully high levels for\nsome time after the recovery\nhas begun.\n3. Both industry and in\ndividuals remain in a cautious,\ncost-cutting mood. With in\nflation still driving prices to\nnew peaks, the consumer has\nlittle incentive to buy. And with\nconsumers saving and skimp\ning. business has little incentive\nto invest in the new plants\nand new products that would\ncreate new jobs.\nHopes Found High\nIn State after State the AP\nfound hopes high for spring\ntime improvement- But those\ninterviewed supplied few solid\nfacts to underpin their hopes.\nAside from the usual upturn in\nfarming and construction.\nThe commonest view is: \u201cour\nrecovery depends on what the\nFederal Government does.\u201d\nThis is curbstone economics, to\nbe sure, but it squares with re\ncent comment by Dr. Arthur\nF. Bums, former chairman of\nPresident Eisenhower\u2019s Coun\ncil of Economic Advisers.\nDr. Bums said the slump will\nbe ended only by \u201cmassive\"\nFederal Government interven\ntion. A temporary tax cut of\nS 4 billion to 85 billion un\ndoubtedly would \u201crevivify the\neconomy,\u201d he said, although\nthis might not be the moment\nfor it. Also helpful, and less\nInflationary. Dr. Burns said,\nwould be public works of a type\nthat could be finished in to\n9 months.\nMr. Eisenhower, his cabinet,\nand his present chief econo\nmist, Dr Raymond J. Sa\\jlnier.\nhave held to the view that nat\nural recovery forces will assert\nthemselves by summer. The\nPresident told his news confer\nence this week that purchases\nby \"millions of citizens\u201d will\nmake the difference.\nMarch Figures Awaited\nThe government, say admin\nistration spokesmen, should\nwait until the March figures\non joblessness become known\n\u2014which will be in April\u2014be\nfore deciding whether rush\nup the oxygen tanks.\nThe latest job count, for mid-\nFebruary. is due to be an\nnounced Tuesday. Secretary of\nLabor Mitchell has already\nforecast it will show 5 million\nor more unemployed, up from\nmid-January\u2019s 4Vs million. It\nis the following month\u2019s data\nthat the administration is\nbanking on to show improve\nment.\nBut heavy pressure is build\ning up on Congress and the\nadministration. Calls for action\nhave been heard from big busi\nness and big labor alike.\nHarlow Curtice, General Mo\ntors Corp. president, has urged\nCongress to consider \u201ca very\nsubstantial tax reduction\u201d this\nsession. Ford Motor Co.\u2019s finan\ncial vice president, T. O. Ynte\nma, has proposed temporary\nsuspension of income tax with\nholding to buoy purchasing\npower.\nThe labor unions see as their\nmission a redoubled effort to\nboost workers\u2019 pay. so they can\nin effect buy their way out of\nthe recession. The unions also\nSimpson Advocates Cut\nOs 10% in Income Taxes\nA 10 per cent cut in personal\nincome tax rates was urged\nlast night by Representative\nSimpson. Republican of Penn\nsylvania. as par t of a general\ntax reduction bill he intends\nto introduce in the House this\nweek.\nMr. Simpson, chairman of\nthe Republican Congressional\nCampaign Committee and a\nmember of the tax-witing\nHouse Ways and Means Com\nmittee, said his measure would\nsave individuals and businesses\n$6 billion.\nBesides the across-the-board\nincome tax cut that would\napply to persons in all brackets,\nother provisions in the bill\nwould:\n1. Set a maximum surtax rate\nof 70 per cent instead of the\npresent 91 per cent on indi\nvidual incomes. Mr. Simpson\nsaid this would save such tax\npayers SB4 million. The 10 per\ncent across-the-board cut in\nIncome tax rates would save\nthem almost $3 billion.\n2. Reduce from 53 to 50 per\ncent the existing Income tax\nrate on corporations, a saving\nof SBOO million for them\nOther Reductions Urged\n3. Allow various tax relief\nprocedures so that small busi\nnesses could save S2OO million\n4.. Repeal the Federal excise\ntax on transportation of prop\nerty. Reduce from 10 per cent\nto 5 per cent the excise tax on\ntransportation of persons. This\nwould save the American people\nS6OO million. Mr. Simpson es\ntimated.\n5. Lower several other excise\ntaxes. These would Include a\n5 per cent rate instead of the\npresent 10 per cent levies on\nautomobiles and 8 per cent on\nparts and accessories. This\nexcise tax relief would amount\nto $1.3 billion. Mr. Simpson\nsaid.\n6. Make the alternative capi\ntal gains tax 12 a per cent\ninstead of the present 25 per\nseek higher job-security de\nfenses against the waves of lay\noffs.\nBut labor is not depending on\nbargaining power alone. The\nAFL-CIO has hired the capi\n-1 tal\u2019s biggest hotel ballroom next\nweek for an emergency eco\nnomic session of 1,000 union\nleaders from all over the Na\ntion. The purpose: \u201cArousing\u201d\nCongress to antirecession moves,\nIncluding a favorite AFL-CIO\naim to boost present individual\nincome tax exemptions.\nLabor\u2019s spring wage drive\npresents two economic hazards\nOne of them has\u2019 been pro\nclaimed repeatedly by officials\nfrom Mr. Eisenhower on down\n\u2014the possibility that 1958 wage\nsettlements will shove record\nhigh prices even higher, thus\nfurther discouraging consumer\nbuying.\nThe other, a source of private\nworry in the administration, is\nthat serious strikes will occur\nwhen the unions come up.\nagainst the stiffening resistance\nof employers who face sagging\nsales and slipping profits. An\nexample of this is the strike of\n106,000 East Coast dressmakers,\nbreaking a quarter century of\nlabor peace.\nBoth sides will bring the\nprice problem to the bargaining\ntable. Living costs have hit new\npeaks in 15 of the past 17\nmonths, and some Government\neconomists now do net expect\na decline before summer or fall,\nif then.\nThe unions argue that wages\nshould go up too. Manage\nments insist that prices cannot\nstabilize until wage increases\nslow down.\nWages Will Increase\nBut wages will go up this\nyear, willy nilly, even if indus\ntry\u2019s total payroll costs are re\nduced by layoffs and shortened\nwork weeks. Seme 4Vi million\nworkers are guaranteed sizable\nboosts, mostly 7 to 10 cents\nan hour, under long-term con\ntracts with built-in annual pay\nincreases.\nThese automatic raises- will\ntend to put a floor under the\ndemands of more than 2 million\nother workers whose unions\nwill be bargaining on new pay\nterms.\nSo 1958 wage increases run\nning into billions of dollars\nannually can be expected.\nWhether they will help or hurt,\nin meeting the immediate\nproblem, remains to be seen.\nSerious strikes almost cer\ntianly would be damaging. An\nauto shutdown, predicted by\nmany, would spread hardship\nand new layoffs among the\nscores of supplying industries\nwhich already are pinched by\nDetroit\u2019s poor sales year.\nWait for Jobs Due\nStrikes or no strikes, the AP\nsurvey suggests that it might\nbe a good many months even\nafter recovery sets in before\nmost laid-off workers are re\nhired in the steel, autos, air\ncraft, furniture, lumber, home\nappliance and other hard-hit\nindustries.\nEmployers, before commenc\ning to rehire, historically have\ntended to restore their reduced\nworking forces to a full-time\nbasis. Low-seniority workers\nmay remain jobless long after\ntheir unemployment compen\nsation runs out.\ncent as a means of increasing)\nthe supply of investment money\nand help to provide more jobs.\nDefends Prop*sals\nExplaining his tax reduction\nplan at a Lincoln Day dimjer\nlast night at Parkersburg. W.j\nVa.. Mr. Simpson declared:\n\u201cThis program is not a com\nmitment to deficit financing. On\nthe contrary it is a corailary\nto the other steps taken by the\nRepublican administration to\nbring about a prompt upturn in\neconomic activity. Instead of\nproducing deficit financing it\nis my prediction that it will\navoid deficit financing in the\nlong run. It will not abandon\nprogressive income tax rates\nnor depart from the traditional\ntax philosophy based on ability\nto pay.\n\"Instead it will lessen stifling\ndeterrents to economic expan\nsion and risk-taking which now\nexist in our tax structure and\nwhich impair the creation of\nnew job opportunities and the\ndevelopment of greater worker\nproductivity.\"\nMr. Simpson said he realized\nthat the \"political demagogue\"\nwill charge that the proposed\ntax reductions would especially\nhelp persons in the higher in\ncome brackets.\n\u201cThe answer to that dema\ngogic charge.\" he said, \"is that\nthe proportionate tax relief\ni under this proposal is the same\nin each income category. The\ntax saving in the higher brack\n!ets is greater in dollar terms\nonly because taxpayers in\nthose categories properly pay\nmore taxes/'\nNarcotics Talk Slated\nLeroy Morrison, an agent of\nthe United States Bureau of\nNarcotics, will address the\nMethodist Men of McKendree\nMethodist Church at 8 p.m\nTuesday in the church. South\nDakota and Rhode Island ave\nnues V. E.\n$1.4 Billion Bill\nOn Rivers Eyed\nAs Spur to Jobs\ni By ROBERT K. WALSH\nStar Stiff Writer\nPleas for public works to aid\nemployment and industry will\nput extra heat in House debate\ntomorrow on a 81.4 billion\nrivers, harbors and floor-con\ntrol authorization bill.\nThe measure, passed by the\nSenate in considerably differ\nent form almost a year ago, has\n1 no immediate relationship to\nproposals outlined yesterday by\nPresident Eisenhower to speed\nup public Improvements already\nauthorized.\n1 It nevertheless offers a timely\ntest of congressional sentiment\non possibly greater expansion\nof such projects. The revised\n1 Senate measure was reported\nI out by the House Public Works\nCommittee last August.\nAs scheduled for debate to\nmorrow and a vote later this\nweek in the House, the bill\ni would appropriate no funds,\ni But it would open the way for\ni appropriations totaling 81.456.-\n637,800 by Congress later this\nyear or in future years by au\nthorizing numerous river and\nharbor projects such as chan\nnel deepening and beach ero\nsion control.\nIncludes Baltimore\nIt includes a 628 million\nauthorization for dredging and\ndeepening Baltimore harbor\nThe bill also would permit flood\ncontrol projects, especially in\nNew England and Middle At\nlantic States hard hit by hurri\ncanes.\nIn its slow progress from the\nSenate since March 28. 1957, to\nthe House floor this week, the\nbill has been tangled in charges\nof too much \u201cpork.\u201d counter\ncharges of \u201cunseemly\u201d inter\nference by the Budget Bureau,\nand predictions that Mr. Eisen\nbower will veto it as he did\nsn a similar bill in 1956.\nBut the President\u2019s impend\ning recommendations, includ\ning a proposal to \u201caccelerate\nwhere practicable the con\nstruction of projects for which\nappropriated funds are avail\nable,\u201d could change the tenor\nof the House debate tomorrow.\nThis, in turn, conceivably could\nresult in individual moves to\namend the authorization bill by\nrestoring the total closer to the\noriginal Senate figure.\nMost Republicans on the\nHouse Public Works Commit\ntee have complained that the\nbill still contains 8303 million\nin proposed projects not rec\nommended by the Budget Bu\nreau and the Army Corps of\nEngineers. They recalled that\nMr. Eisenhower had the same\nobjections when he vetoed a\nsimilar' version, totaling more\nthan 81.6 billion, in 1956.\nObtained Later Data\nCommittee Chairman Buck\nley. Democrat of Ohio, and his\nmajority colleagues hope many\nof the President\u2019s 1956 objec\ntions have been removed be\ncause House and Senate com\nmittees obtained later reports\nfrom the agencies.\nThey note that the bill passed\nby the Senate a year ago would\nhave authorized 81.542.452.000,\na reduction of almost $77 mil\nlion below the 1956 bill. The\nHouse committee, in reporting\nout a revised bill last August,\ntrimmed an additional SBS mil\nlion to bring the total down to\n$1.4 billion.\nBoth sides believe the House\nwill pass an authorization bill\nbut not necessarily the House\ncommittee\u2019s recommendation or\nthe Senate\u2019s measure. The real'\nshowdown on public works\nprojects of this kind will come\nwhen the Appropriations Com\nmittee reports out a bill to pro\nvide the money.\nProbe Is Urged\nIn News 'Leak'\nBy the Asioclated Press\nRepresentative Patman, Dem-!\nocrat of Texas, said yesterday\nword of a reduction in the Fed\neral Reserve\u2019s discount rate\nwas leaked in advance. As a\nresult, he said, some securities\ndealers \u201cmust have really\ncleaned up a profit.\u201d\nMr. Patman demanded an in\nquiry by the House Banking\nCommittee. A similar demand\nwas made Friday night by Rep\nresentative Multer, Democrat of\nNew York, another member of\nthe banking group.\nHowever, Chairman Spence of\ntne Banking Committee adopted\na wait-and-see attitude on Mr j\nPatman\u2019s statement, made in'\nChicago.\n\u201cI don\u2019t know what his evi\ndence is but if he has sub\nstantial evidence <of a leak) 1\nthink it\u2019s all right to investi\ngate,\u201d Mr. Spence said.\nReturning to Washington, Mr\nI Patman told a newsman \"no\nbody has that evidence.\u201d But\nhe said the market on Gov\nernment bonds went up Just\nbefore the discount rate reduc\ntion was announced by the Fed\neral Reserve Board Thursday\nThat\u2019s enough to arouse our\ncuriosity.\u201d Mr. Patman said.\nHe said the stock market also\nrose just before the Reserve\nBoard announced a reduction\nin margin requirements on\nstock purchases in mid-January\nThere was no comment from\nthe Reserve Board.\nPsychiatrist to Talk\nDr. Jerome D. Frank. Bal\ntimore psychiatrist, will speak\non \u201cReason and Emotion in a\nNuclear Age\" at Lisner Audi\ntorium, Twenty-first and H\nstreets N.W., on Thursday at\n8 p.m. The meeting, open to\nthe public, is sponsored by Psl\nChi. the George Washington\nUniversity Psychology Honor\nlary Society.\nAnalyst Ranks Recession\nWith Others Since 1949\nNEW YORK. Mar. 8 (A*).\u2014A\nleading business-cycle analyst\nsays statistical indicators show\nthe current recession may be\nat least as severe as those of\n1949-50 and 1953-54, and per\nhaps more so.\nBut it is not likely to be as\nsevere as the depression that\nbegan in 1929 or the 1937-38\nrecession, says Dr. Geoffrey H.\nMoore, associate director of re\nsearch for the National Bureau\nof Economic Research.\nThe bureau is a private re\nsearch agency controlled by\nleading universities and pro\nfess ional organizations. Dr.\nMoore\u2019s studies of indicators of\neconomic recessions and re\nvivals are based on data on all\nBHIMKfII\nHEN Witt no\nEnter MOTOROLA'S New Tube Sentry Contest\nP ,ntfy twn\" *t you, Mfflwoti .IM*\nStyled with clean, thin lines, this budget-priced set offers\nall the new Motorola advances for \u2019SB. Exclusive Tube\nSentry protection Power M Chassis... Right-Up-Front\nTuning 20,000-Volt Picture Power. And wait\u2019ll you see\nthe low, low price Motorola has put on this dependable TV.\nModel 21T47. (Base optional, extra.) 21' over-all diagonal\npicture tube with 263 sq. in. viewing area.\n*179\u201d\nAWv Made! 21T4?\nin CKorceot fmi?b\n\nR